aa(lp207
VWell, to do that, one thing is we can look at the deception-detection literature.
p208
aVIt's a very old literature by now, it's coming up on 50 years.
p209
aVIt's been reviewed many times. There's been thousands of trials,
p210
aVhundreds of studies, and there's some really compelling findings.
p211
aa(lp212
VThe first is, we're really bad at detecting deception,
p213
aVreally bad. Fifty-four percent accuracy on average when you have to tell
p214
aVif somebody that just said a statement is lying or not.
p215
aVThat's really bad. Why is it so bad?
p216
aVWell it has to do with Pinocchio's nose.
p217
aVIf I were to ask you guys, what do you rely on
p218
aVwhen you're looking at somebody and you want to find out
p219
aVif they're lying? What cue do you pay attention to?
p220
aVMost of you would say that one of the cues you look at
p221
aVis the eyes. The eyes are the window to the soul.
p222
aVAnd you're not alone. Around the world, almost every culture,
p223
aVone of the top cues is eyes. But the research
p224
aVover the last 50 years says there's actually no reliable cue
p225
aVto deception, which blew me away, and it's one of
p226
aVthe hard lessons that I learned when I was customs officer.
p227
aVThe eyes do not tell us whether somebody's lying or not.
p228
aVSome situations, yes \u2014 high stakes, maybe their pupils dilate,
p229
aVtheir pitch goes up, their body movements change a little bit,
p230
aVbut not all the time, not for everybody, it's not reliable.
p231
aVStrange. The other thing is that just because you can't see me
p232
aVdoesn't mean I'm going to lie. It's common sense,
p233
aVbut one important finding is that we lie for a reason.
p234
aVWe lie to protect ourselves or for our own gain
p235
aVor for somebody else's gain.
p236
aVSo there are some pathological liars, but they make up
p237
aVa tiny portion of the population. We lie for a reason.
p238
aVJust because people can't see us doesn't mean
p239
aVwe're going to necessarily lie.
p240
aa(lp241
VBut I think there's actually something much more
p242
aVinteresting and fundamental going on here. The next big
p243
aVthing for me, the next big idea, we can find by going
p244
aVway back in history to the origins of language.
p245
aVMost linguists agree that we started speaking somewhere
p246
aVbetween 50,000 and 100,000 years ago. That's a long time ago.
p247
aVA lot of humans have lived since then.
p248
aVWe've been talking, I guess, about fires and caves
p249
aVand saber-toothed tigers. I don't know what they talked about,
p250
aVbut they were doing a lot of talking, and like I said,
p251
aVthere's a lot of humans evolving speaking,
p252
aVabout 100 billion people in fact.
p253
aVWhat's important though is that writing only emerged
p254
aVabout 5,000 years ago. So what that means is that
p255
aVall the people before there was any writing,
p256
aVevery word that they ever said, every utterance
p257
aVdisappeared. No trace. Evanescent. Gone.
p258
aVSo we've been evolving to talk in a way in which
p259
aVthere is no record. In fact, even the next big change
p260
aVto writing was only 500 years ago now,
p261
aVwith the printing press, which is very recent in our past,
p262
aVand literacy rates remained incredibly low right up until World War II,
p263
aVso even the people of the last two millennia,
p264
aVmost of the words they ever said \u2014 poof! \u2014 disappeared.
