aa(lp266
VLet's turn to now, the networked age.
p267
aVHow many of you have recorded something today?
p268
aVAnybody do any writing today? Did anybody write a word?
p269
aVIt looks like almost every single person here recorded something.
p270
aVIn this room, right now, we've probably recorded more
p271
aVthan almost all of human pre-ancient history.
p272
aVThat is crazy. We're entering this amazing period
p273
aVof flux in human evolution where we've evolved to speak
p274
aVin a way in which our words disappear, but we're in
p275
aVan environment where we're recording everything.
p276
aVIn fact, I think in the very near future, it's not just
p277
aVwhat we write that will be recorded, everything we do
p278
aVwill be recorded.
p279
aVWhat does that mean? What's the next big idea from that?
p280
aVWell, as a social scientist, this is the most amazing thing
p281
aVI have ever even dreamed of. Now, I can look at
p282
aVall those words that used to, for millennia, disappear.
p283
aVI can look at lies that before were said and then gone.
p284
aVYou remember those Astroturfing reviews that we were
p285
aVtalking about before? Well, when they write a fake review,
p286
aVthey have to post it somewhere, and it's left behind for us.
